{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17603206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17603206"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:34:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:34:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15723"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15723"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8414"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62885"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8414"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15723"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48335"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"1353"},{"type":"tags","id":"1627"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7037"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20265"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62885"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about irregular periods and excess facial hair. Her periods occur every two to three months. She has gained 10 kg over the past year despite no changes to her diet. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 32 kg/m2. There is notable hirsutism on her face and abdomen. Abdominal examination reveals no masses or tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Polycystic ovary syndrome","Congenital adrenal hyperplasia","Cushing syndrome","Hypothyroidism","Ovarian tumour"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), including oligomenorrhoea, hirsutism, and obesity. \u003Cstrong\u003EPolycystic ovary syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common endocrine disorder in women of reproductive age, affecting 8-13% of this population. The diagnosis requires two of three Rotterdam criteria: oligo/anovulation, clinical or biochemical hyperandrogenism, and polycystic ovaries on ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital adrenal hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents in infancy or early childhood with virilisation. Late-onset forms can present similarly to PCOS but are much less common.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECushing syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with more specific features such as central obesity, purple striae, proximal muscle weakness, and easy bruising, which are not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E can cause menstrual irregularities and weight gain but would not typically cause hirsutism. Other features like cold intolerance, fatigue, and dry skin would be expected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian tumours\u003C/strong\u003E causing androgen excess are rare and typically cause rapid onset of virilisation with more severe symptoms than seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of PCOS involves lifestyle modifications for weight loss, combined oral contraceptive pills to regulate periods and reduce androgens, and metformin if there are metabolic features. Regular screening for complications such as diabetes, dyslipidaemia, and endometrial hyperplasia is important.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Polycystic ovary syndrome affects 8-13% of reproductive-age women and is the most common endocrine disorder in this population.","Key diagnostic features of PCOS include oligomenorrhoea, hyperandrogenism, and polycystic ovaries on ultrasound.","PCOS is associated with increased risk of metabolic syndrome, type 2 diabetes, and cardiovascular disease."],"references":["Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Witchel SF, Oberfield SE, Pe\u00f1a AS. Polycystic Ovary Syndrome: Pathophysiology, Presentation, and Treatment With Emphasis on Adolescent Girls. J Endocr Soc. 2019 Jun 14;3(8):1545-1573. doi: 10.1210/js.2019-00078. PMID: 31384717; PMCID: PMC6676075.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences.","Singh S, Pal N, Shubham S, Sarma DK, Verma V, Marotta F, Kumar M. Polycystic Ovary Syndrome: Etiology, Current Management, and Future Therapeutics. J Clin Med. 2023 Feb 11;12(4):1454. doi: 10.3390/jcm12041454. PMID: 36835989; PMCID: PMC9964744."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48335"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15723"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48335"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T08:29:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T08:30:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8414"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"628